As the summary above, there are some columns that contain (mostly) only null data. In addition, there are some columns that do not have nay contribution to the prediction such as weather_description, weather_main, icon, etc. Therefore, the first step is to remove all useless, redundant columns from the data frame.

As shown in the table above, data were collected also during the night. These stats do not have any meaning since there is no sun, thus no energy generated at night. Futhermore, having them in the training dataset can significantly reduce the quality of the model. Assuming that there is completely no sun between 22:00 and 04:00 of the next day, rows whose 'clock' belongs to this time interval are removed:

The solar energy production data published by Frank (https://www.kaggle.com/fvcoppen/solarpanelspower) contains only daily data. Therefore data in the dataframe above which were collected in the same day need to be gather together into a single rows. There are two options to do this: 1) Make columns of every hour in a day and 2) Calculate the value for morning, noon and afternoon.

The choice should be made based on the weather forecast given by OpenWeather. There are two types of data: 1) One Call API that gives hourly forecast for 48 hours and 2) 5 Day / 3 Hour forecast, where The API response is the forecast of 3 hours for the next 5 days.

For now, the second option is used to predict the solar energy 5 day ahead. The data will be averaged out whithin 3 time frames: 04:00 to 11:00, 11:00 to 16:00, and 16:00 to 22:00. Note that weather_id is categorical data, it will not be averaged but the most popular data will be taken instead.

In [10]:
#To find the value with the most apperance
from collections import Counter

def most_frequent(lst):
    data = Counter(lst)
    return data.most_common(1)[0][0]
In [11]:
def simplify_data(weather):
    new_data = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['date',
                                       'mor_temp','mor_humid','mor_wspd','mor_wdeg','mor_cloud','mor_weather_id',
                                       'noo_temp','noo_humid','noo_wspd','noo_wdeg','noo_cloud','noo_weather_id',
                                       'aft_temp','aft_humid','aft_wspd','aft_wdeg','aft_cloud','aft_weather_id',])
    
    mor_count, mor_temp, mor_humid, mor_wspd, mor_wdeg, mor_cloud = [0]*6
    noo_count, noo_temp, noo_humid, noo_wspd, noo_wdeg, noo_cloud = [0]*6
    aft_count, aft_temp, aft_humid, aft_wspd, aft_wdeg, aft_cloud = [0]*6
    
    mor_weather_id=[]
    noo_weather_id=[]
    aft_weather_id=[]
    
    current_date = weather.loc[0, 'dt_iso'][0:10]
    
    for i in range(len(weather)):
        if weather.loc[i, 'dt_iso'][0:10] != current_date:
            new_data = new_data.append({
                'date':current_date,
                'mor_temp':mor_temp/mor_count,
                'mor_humid':mor_humid/mor_count,
                'mor_wspd':mor_wspd/mor_count,
                'mor_wdeg':mor_wdeg/mor_count,
                'mor_cloud':mor_cloud/mor_count,
                'mor_weather_id':most_frequent(mor_weather_id),
                'noo_temp':noo_temp/noo_count,
                'noo_humid':noo_humid/noo_count,
                'noo_wspd':noo_wspd/noo_count,
                'noo_wdeg':noo_wdeg/noo_count,
                'noo_cloud':noo_cloud/noo_count,
                'noo_weather_id':most_frequent(noo_weather_id),
                'aft_temp':aft_temp/aft_count,
                'aft_humid':aft_humid/aft_count,
                'aft_wspd':aft_wspd/aft_count,
                'aft_wdeg':aft_wdeg/aft_count,
                'aft_cloud':aft_cloud/aft_count,
                'aft_weather_id':most_frequent(aft_weather_id)
            }, ignore_index=True)
            
            mor_count, mor_temp, mor_humid, mor_wspd, mor_wdeg, mor_cloud = [0]*6
            noo_count, noo_temp, noo_humid, noo_wspd, noo_wdeg, noo_cloud = [0]*6
            aft_count, aft_temp, aft_humid, aft_wspd, aft_wdeg, aft_cloud = [0]*6
            
            mor_weather_id=[]
            noo_weather_id=[]
            aft_weather_id=[]
    
            current_date = weather.loc[i, 'dt_iso'][0:10]
        
        if int(weather.loc[i, 'dt_iso'][11:13]) < 11:
            mor_count += 1
            mor_temp += weather.loc[i, 'temp']
            mor_humid += weather.loc[i, 'humidity']
            mor_wspd += weather.loc[i, 'wind_speed']
            mor_wdeg += weather.loc[i, 'wind_deg']
            mor_cloud += weather.loc[i, 'clouds_all']
            mor_weather_id.append(weather['weather_id'][i])
            
        elif int(weather.loc[i, 'dt_iso'][11:13]) < 16:
            noo_count += 1
            noo_temp += weather.loc[i, 'temp']
            noo_humid += weather.loc[i, 'humidity']
            noo_wspd += weather.loc[i, 'wind_speed']
            noo_wdeg += weather.loc[i, 'wind_deg']
            noo_cloud += weather.loc[i, 'clouds_all']
            noo_weather_id.append(weather['weather_id'][i])
            
        else:
            aft_count += 1
            aft_temp += weather.loc[i, 'temp']
            aft_humid += weather.loc[i, 'humidity']
            aft_wspd += weather.loc[i, 'wind_speed']
            aft_wdeg += weather.loc[i, 'wind_deg']
            aft_cloud += weather.loc[i, 'clouds_all']
            aft_weather_id.append(weather['weather_id'][i])
        
    return new_data

According to the description of the dataset, data were recorded at the beginning of days. Therfore, the info in the table actually describes the cum_power in the previous day. Since the purpose of this project is to find out the relationship between weather and daily energy production, the daily number also needs to be calculated from accumulate data.

In [22]:
energy = energy.shift(periods=-1, freq='D', axis=0) #step one day back

power_list = [0] * len(energy)
power_list[0] = energy['cum_power'][0]

for i in range(len(energy)-1):
    power_list[i+1] = energy['cum_power'][i+1] - energy['cum_power'][i]

energy.insert(1, "daily_power", power_list, True)
energy.drop(labels='cum_power', axis=1, inplace=True)
